  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. It is widely recognized as a crime because it facilitates other illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and organized crime, by allowing criminals to profit from their illicit activities and integrate those profits into the legitimate financial system.\n\nMost countries have established laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF). These laws typically require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities, maintain records, and verify the identities of their customers. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences.\n\nAdditionally, international cooperation and information sharing among countries are crucial in the fight against money laundering, as it often involves cross-border transactions and multiple jurisdictions. Treaties and agreements, such as the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC) and the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC), further reinforce the global consensus that money laundering is illegal and must be combated collectively.",
